                                Below is a concise, rephrased English version formatted like an academic program or list of specializations within an Engineering degree. I preserved the accreditation code you provided.
Engineering Major
Engineers apply science, mathematics, analysis and synthesis to design practical, efficient solutions within constraints of time, cost, safety and health. The degree prepares graduates for roles in design, research, operation and project management across industries.


Aerospace (Aeronautical) EngineeringStudy aircraft and spacecraft design, aerodynamics, airfoil and control-surface design, lift and drag, and flight/spacecraft systems. Covers aerodynamic behavior, propulsion basics and vehicle control.


Applied ScienceApply natural science principles to solve practical problems and develop technology. Prepares students for science careers and professional/graduate studies (e.g., medicine, pharmacy, optometry, veterinary, physical therapy).


Chemical / Petroleum EngineeringFocus on the exploration, extraction and production of oil and gas, and on chemical process engineering. Emphasizes reservoir evaluation, drilling supervision, production optimization, environmental safety and development of extraction technologies.


Civil EngineeringDesign, construct and maintain built and natural environments. Specializations include structural, geotechnical, transportation, water resources, environmental, urban/coastal engineering, materials engineering, surveying and construction management.


Electrical / Electronic EngineeringStudy electricity, electronics and electromagnetism. Topics include power systems, transmission and distribution, control systems, signal processing, telecommunications, integrated circuits and electronic device design.


Mechanical EngineeringCover mechanics, kinematics, thermodynamics, heat transfer, fluid mechanics, robotics, structural analysis and technical drafting. Emphasis on design, energy conversion, machine systems and mechanical product development.


